() Tj
T*
(4. End-to-End Flow) Tj
T*
(From an end-to-end perspective, the recruiter logs in, provides the job description, uploads) Tj
T*
(CVs, and submits the batch. The React frontend sends the data to the ASP.NET backend using) Tj
T*
(multipart form data. The backend parses the files, extracts candidate information, calls the) Tj
T*
(ranking logic or AI ranking service, and generates a ranking report. The frontend then) Tj
T*
(retrieves the report and displays the ranked candidates with explanations and percentage) Tj
T*
(matches.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(5. Key Technical Highlights) Tj
T*
(A few technical areas I focused on were authentication, multi-file upload handling, PDF text) Tj
T*
(extraction, candidate ranking logic, and frontend usability. I also added progress feedback) Tj
T*
(in the UI so users can see the ranking process while the backend is working. On the backend) Tj
T*
(side, I used service-based design so that authentication, screening, and AI ranking remain) Tj
T*
(separate concerns. That makes the project easier to maintain and extend.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(6. Why This Project Is Valuable) Tj
T*
(This project demonstrates full-stack engineering skills because it includes frontend UI) Tj
T*
(design, backend API development, authentication, document processing, AI integration,) Tj
T*
(ranking logic, and recruiter-focused workflow design. It is also a practical product idea) Tj
T*
(because it addresses a real business problem in hiring efficiency and candidate evaluation.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(7. Limitations And Future Improvements) Tj
T*
(Right now, the project is a strong prototype. The backend still uses in-memory storage, so) Tj
T*
(one improvement would be moving to a persistent database such as SQL Server. Another) Tj
T*
